    "body": "### Problem\n\nI use xxd in neovim to deal with binary files.\nI find `:%!xxd` will give the incorrect result (the dumped file size is much larger than the actual), by inspecting the source code, I find it is because `Get-Content` is used to retrieve the buffer's content (the buffer content is stored in a temp file, for PowerShell v7 `-AsByteStream` should be used to deal with binary files), garbling the binary content.\n\n<https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e3fd906b614c9ef0fdca3e456b75eae34086555b/src/nvim/ex_cmds.c#L1580>\n\nThe above issue is due to the usage of  `Get-Content` (with default UTF-8 encoding since v7) to read the temp buffer file. Since temp files are used when `shelltemp` is set, so I turn to `noshelltemp` to see if I can bypass this issue, and it works well, but with one issue illustrated below:\n\n<https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/72785ba2-7daf-4ca2-abd1-4a89dba54fde>\n\nIn the error message `xxd` is truncated to `xx`, which is very strange.\nThen I test with `:%!xxd && Start-Sleep 114514`, and in the task manager, we see that the last character `4` is truncated. Currently the workaround is to append a dummy character at the end of the command.\n\n<img width=\"1018\" height=\"997\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fecac020-1c47-429d-abb6-283756180664\" />\n\nSuch issue may relate to the potentially problematic code below (buf size `len` may be insufficient to accommodate the command):\n\n<https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e3fd906b614c9ef0fdca3e456b75eae34086555b/src/nvim/ex_cmds.c#L1579-L1590>\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nThe minimal config:\n\n```lua\nvim.o.shell = \"pwsh\"\nvim.o.shellcmdflag = [[-NoLogo -NoProfile -NonInteractive -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Command]]\nvim.o.shelltemp = false -- use pipes instead of temp files\nvim.o.shellquote = \"\"\nvim.o.shellxquote = \"\"\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`:%!xxd` runs normally.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.11.3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nHaven't tested yet, but highly possible.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11 24H2\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nwinget",
